Build and deploy a stroke prediction model using R

Olapeju Esuola

April 25, 2024

About Data Analysis Report

This RMarkdown file contains the report of the data analysis done for the project on building and deploying a stroke prediction model in R. It contains analysis such as data exploration, summary statistics and building the prediction models. The final report was completed on April 25, 2024.

Data Description:

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) stroke is the 2nd leading cause of death globally, responsible for approximately 11% of total deaths.

This data set is used to predict whether a patient is likely to get stroke based on the input parameters like gender, age, various diseases, and smoking status. Each row in the data provides relevant information about the patient.

Project Context

The escalating prevalence of strokes poses a significant challenge to healthcare systems worldwide. Recognizing the imperative for preemptive measures, our organization endeavors to harness advanced analytics and machine learning to predict stroke occurrences accurately. Through the integration of predictive models into clinical workflows, we aim to identify high-risk patients promptly and implement targeted preventive interventions.

Project Objectives

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Investigate the dataset to discern critical patient and clinical attributes associated with stroke incidence. Model Development: Develop a validated stroke prediction model capable of informing clinical decision-making processes effectively. Model Deployment: Integrate the prediction model into the organization’s clinical infrastructure to enhance patient care and outcomes.

Based on the information provided after loading the dataset and examining the first few rows using the head() function, here is the description of the dataset:

ID: Unique identifier for each observation. Gender: Categorical variable indicating the gender of the individual. Age: Numerical variable representing the age of the individual. Hypertension: Binary variable (0 or 1) indicating whether the individual has hypertension. Heart Disease: Binary variable (0 or 1) indicating whether the individual has heart disease. Ever Married: Categorical variable indicating whether the individual is married. Work Type: Categorical variable representing the type of work the individual is engaged in. Residence Type: Categorical variable indicating whether the individual resides in an urban or rural area. Average Glucose Level: Numerical variable representing the average glucose level of the individual. BMI: Body Mass Index of the individual. Smoking Status: Categorical variable indicating the smoking status of the individual. Stroke: Binary variable (0 or 1) indicating whether the individual had a stroke.

After conducting a thorough analysis of the dataset’s structure, I discovered that the BMI column contained “N/A” values, representing missing values. To address this issue, I first converted the BMI column from character to numeric. Then, I proceeded to drop rows containing “N/A” values in the BMI column. Furthermore, I performed a check on the entire dataset to identify similar situations, and it appears that the dataset is now clean from missing values.

After employing boxplots to detect outliers, it was observed that both the BMI and glucose level variables contain outliers. Given that BMI and glucose levels are physiological measures that can naturally exhibit wide variation among individuals, I have decided not to treat these outliers. This decision is based on the understanding that outliers in these variables may represent genuine data points and removing them could potentially lead to the loss of valuable information. Therefore, I will proceed with the analysis without outlier treatment for the BMI and glucose level variables.

The dataset reveals a notable prevalence of certain characteristics: a higher representation of females, individuals without hypertension or heart disease, married individuals, those with a private work class, urban residents slightly outnumbering rural residents, individuals who have never smoked, and a majority of individuals without a history of stroke.

During my data visualization exploration, I observed that a significant number of individuals did not provide information under the smoking_status column, and it was recorded as “Unknown.” Recognizing the importance of this variable and since I have a large dataset, I have decided to convert “Unknown” values to “NA” and drop rows with missing values.

library(dplyr)

# Compute correlation matrix
correlation_matrix <- cor(stroke_data[sapply(stroke_data, is.numeric)])

corrplot(correlation_matrix, method = "number", type = "upper", tl.col = "black")

After visualizing the correlation matrix, I observed that there is a weak positive correlation between age and stroke (r = 0.24). This suggests that older individuals may have a slightly higher likelihood of experiencing a stroke.

Additionally, I found weak positive correlations between stroke and hypertension, heart disease, and average glucose level (r = 0.14). This implies that individuals with hypertension, heart disease, or higher average glucose levels may have a slightly elevated risk of stroke.

However, there was no significant linear relationship observed between BMI and stroke, as indicated by a blank cell in the correlation matrix. This suggests that BMI may not be strongly associated with the likelihood of experiencing a stroke.

# Assessing the relationship for categorical independent variables:
# Chi-squared test or Fisher's exact test
chi_squared1 <- chisq.test(stroke_data$gender, stroke_data$stroke)
chi_squared1
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  stroke_data$gender and stroke_data$stroke
## X-squared = 0.58334, df = 2, p-value = 0.747
# Visualize the distribution of stroke within each category of the independent variable
ggplot(stroke_data, aes(x = gender, fill = factor(stroke))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Proportion of Stroke")

The Pearson’s chi-squared test was conducted to assess the relationship between gender and stroke in the dataset. The test statistic obtained was X-squared = 0.58334, with 2 degrees of freedom. The corresponding p-value was found to be 0.747.

Since the p-value (0.747) is greater than the significance level (commonly set at 0.05), we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is no significant association between gender and stroke in the dataset.

Since the visualization indicates that the proportion of males and females is similar, it aligns with the results of the Pearson’s chi-squared test, which suggests that gender is not significantly associated with stroke in the dataset.

This consistency between the visualization and statistical test reinforces the conclusion that gender may not be a significant factor influencing the likelihood of experiencing a stroke in the analyzed dataset.

# Assessing the relationship for categorical independent variables:
# Chi-squared test or Fisher's exact test
chi_squared2 <- chisq.test(stroke_data$ever_married, stroke_data$stroke)
chi_squared2
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  stroke_data$ever_married and stroke_data$stroke
## X-squared = 16.865, df = 1, p-value = 4.013e-05
# Visualize the distribution of stroke within each category of the independent variable
ggplot(stroke_data, aes(x = ever_married, fill = factor(stroke))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(x = "Ever Married", y = "Proportion of Stroke")

The Pearson’s chi-squared test with Yates’ continuity correction was conducted to evaluate the relationship between the marital status (ever_married) and stroke in the dataset. The test yielded a chi-squared statistic of X-squared = 16.865, with 1 degree of freedom, and a corresponding p-value of 4.013e-05.

Since the p-value (4.013e-05) is much less than the significance level (commonly set at 0.05), we reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is a significant association between marital status and stroke in the dataset.

The visualization showing a higher proportion of individuals who are “ever married” compared to those who are not aligns with the results of the Pearson’s chi-squared test with Yates’ continuity correction.

The statistical test indicates a significant association between marital status (ever_married) and stroke, with a lower p-value suggesting that the observed difference in proportions is unlikely to have occurred by chance.

This consistency between the visualization and statistical analysis strengthens the conclusion that marital status may indeed be a significant factor influencing the likelihood of experiencing a stroke in the dataset.

# For numerical independent variables:
# T-test
# Subset the data for individuals with stroke and without stroke
age_with_stroke <- stroke_data$age[stroke_data$stroke == 1]
age_without_stroke <- stroke_data$age[stroke_data$stroke == 0]

# Perform independent t-test
t_test_result1 <- t.test(age_with_stroke, age_without_stroke)

# View the result
t_test_result1
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age_with_stroke and age_without_stroke
## t = 21.701, df = 230.57, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  18.62597 22.34590
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  68.05556  47.56962
# Create boxplot
ggplot(stroke_data, aes(x = factor(stroke), y = age, fill = factor(stroke))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Age by Stroke Status",
       x = "Stroke Status",
       y = "Age",
       fill = "Stroke Status") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("0" = "blue", "1" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal()

The p-value obtained from the Welch Two Sample t-test is highly significant (p < 2.2e-16), indicating a substantial difference in the mean age between individuals with and without stroke. This suggests strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the observed difference in mean age is unlikely to have occurred by random chance alone. Therefore, age appears to be a significant factor associated with the likelihood of experiencing a stroke. Specifically, the significantly higher mean age among individuals with stroke compared to those without stroke suggests that older age may be a risk factor for stroke occurrence.

In summary, the low p-value suggests that age is likely to be an important predictor of stroke incidence, with older individuals being more susceptible to experiencing a stroke.

# For numerical independent variables:
# T-test
# Subset the data for individuals with stroke and without stroke
avg_glucose_level_with_stroke <- stroke_data$avg_glucose_level[stroke_data$stroke == 1]
avg_glucose_level_without_stroke <- stroke_data$avg_glucose_level[stroke_data$stroke == 0]

# Perform independent t-test
t_test_result2 <- t.test(avg_glucose_level_with_stroke, avg_glucose_level_without_stroke)

# View the result
t_test_result2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  avg_glucose_level_with_stroke and avg_glucose_level_without_stroke
## t = 6.2787, df = 189.74, p-value = 2.272e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  20.59266 39.45885
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  136.7701  106.7444
# Create boxplot
ggplot(stroke_data, aes(x = factor(stroke), y = avg_glucose_level, fill = factor(stroke))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Average Glucose Level by Stroke Status",
       x = "Stroke Status",
       y = "Distribution of Average Glucose Level by Stroke Status",
       fill = "Stroke Status") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("0" = "blue", "1" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal()

The p-value obtained from the Welch Two Sample t-test is extremely small (p = 2.272e-09), indicating a highly significant difference in the mean glucose levels between individuals with and without stroke. This suggests strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the observed difference in mean glucose levels is unlikely to have occurred by random chance alone. Therefore, glucose level appears to be a significant factor associated with the likelihood of experiencing a stroke.

The 95% confidence interval for the difference in mean glucose levels between the two groups ranges from 20.59 to 39.46 units. This interval suggests that, on average, individuals with stroke have significantly higher glucose levels compared to those without stroke.

The observation from the visualization, showing that individuals with higher glucose levels tend to have a stroke, is consistent with the statistical analysis results. This supports the notion that elevated glucose levels may be a risk factor for stroke incidence.

In summary, the low p-value and the wide confidence interval suggest that glucose level is likely to be an important predictor of stroke incidence, with higher glucose levels being associated with an increased risk of experiencing a stroke.

  labs(title = "Distribution of BMI by Stroke Status",
       x = "Stroke Status",
       y = "Distribution of BMI by Stroke Status",
       fill = "Stroke Status") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("0" = "blue", "1" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal()

The p-value obtained from the Welch Two Sample t-test for BMI (Body Mass Index) is not significant (p = 0.4349), indicating that there is not a statistically significant difference in the mean BMI between individuals with and without stroke. This suggests that the observed difference in mean BMI is likely to have occurred by random chance alone, and there may not be a strong association between BMI and stroke incidence.

The 95% confidence interval for the difference in mean BMI between the two groups ranges from -0.58 to 1.34 units. This interval includes zero, further indicating that there is no substantial difference in mean BMI between individuals with and without stroke.

The observation from the visualization, showing that there is not much difference in BMI between individuals with and without stroke, aligns with the statistical analysis results.

In summary, based on the p-value and confidence interval, it appears that BMI may not be a significant predictor of stroke incidence in this dataset.

Task Two: Build prediction models

# Data Pre-processing 
# Drop the ID column
stroke_data <- stroke_data[, -1]  # ID column is the first column

# Convert categorical variables to factors
stroke_data$gender <- factor(stroke_data$gender)
stroke_data$ever_married <- factor(stroke_data$ever_married)
stroke_data$work_type <- factor(stroke_data$work_type)
stroke_data$Residence_type <- factor(stroke_data$Residence_type)
stroke_data$smoking_status <- factor(stroke_data$smoking_status)
stroke_data$stroke <- factor(stroke_data$stroke)
stroke_data$BMI_Category <- factor(stroke_data$BMI_Category)
stroke_data$hypertension <- factor(stroke_data$hypertension)
stroke_data$heart_disease <- factor(stroke_data$heart_disease)

# Standardize numeric variables
numeric_vars1 <- c("age", "avg_glucose_level", "bmi")
stroke_data[numeric_vars1] <- scale(stroke_data[numeric_vars1])

#Split the Data into Train and Test Sets
# use the caret package to split the data into training and testing sets.

#install.packages("caret")
library(caret)

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Split the data into train (80%) and test (20%) sets
train_index <- createDataPartition(stroke_data$stroke, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- stroke_data[train_index, ]
test_data <- stroke_data[-train_index, ]

#install.packages("e1071")

library(e1071) # For Naive Bayes


# Train Naive Bayes model
nb_model <- naiveBayes(stroke ~ ., data = train_data)

Task Three: Evaluate and select prediction models

# Evaluate the model
# Install and load the pROC package
# install.packages("pROC")
library(pROC)

# Calculate ROC curve and AUC for Naive Bayes model predictions
nb_pred <- predict(nb_model, newdata = test_data, type = "raw")[, 2]
nb_roc <- roc(test_data$stroke, nb_pred)

# Plot ROC curve
plot(nb_roc, main = "ROC Curve for Naive Bayes Model", col = "blue")

# Calculate AUC
nb_auc <- auc(nb_roc)
print(paste("AUC for Naive Bayes Model:", round(nb_auc, 3)))
## [1] "AUC for Naive Bayes Model: 0.81"

An AUC value of 0.81 indicates that the Naive Bayes model has good discriminatory power in distinguishing between positive and negative classes (in this case, individuals who had a stroke and those who did not). Typically, an AUC value above 0.8 is considered very good for a predictive model. It suggests that the model performs well in ranking instances by their likelihood of having a stroke.

# Decision Tree
# Load the rpart package
library(rpart)

# Build the decision tree model
tree_model <- rpart(stroke ~ ., data = train_data, method = "class")

# Make predictions on the test data
tree_pred <- predict(tree_model, newdata = test_data, type = "class")

# Evaluate the model
tree_accuracy <- sum(tree_pred == test_data$stroke) / nrow(test_data)
tree_accuracy
## [1] 0.9474453
# Visualize feature importance
#install.packages("vip")
library(vip)
# Calculate feature importance
importance <- tree_model$variable.importance

# Plot feature importance
barplot(importance, main = "Decision Tree Feature Importance", col = "blue", las = 2)

The decision tree model achieved an accuracy of approximately 94.74% on the test data. This means that the model correctly predicted the stroke status for about 94.74% of the individuals in the test dataset.

From the feature importance visual, age is a significant factor in determining the likelihood of a stroke occurrence.

# Evaluate accuracy
tree_accuracy <- mean(tree_pred == test_data$stroke)
nb_accuracy <- mean(nb_pred == test_data$stroke)

# Compare accuracies
if (tree_accuracy > nb_accuracy) {
  print("Decision Tree has higher accuracy.")
} else if (tree_accuracy < nb_accuracy) {
  print("Naive Bayes has higher accuracy.")
} else {
  print("Both models have the same accuracy.")
}
